-- PRESS DIGEST - Russia - March 14
-- 
-- Fri Mar 14, 2014 05:14AM EDT
-- None



MOSCOW, March 14 (Reuters) - The following are some of the leading stories in Russia's newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

VEDOMOSTI www.vedomosti.ru - Russia is considering ways to expand cooperation with China and Southeast Asia to respond to possible economic sanction from the West. - Russia's biggest private bank, Alfa Bank, has urged Mechel to pay back its $150 million loan within a week, the daily says suggesting only the government was able to save the heavily indebted steel and coal group from default. - Russia has intensified training of the combat ability of its troops located close to the border with Ukraine, the daily says citing military sources.   KOMMERSANT www.kommersant.ru - Russia's Gazprom <GAZP.MM> and Rosneft <ROSN.MM> have refused to discuss the situation with Crimean oil and gas fields which local authorities are planning to nationalise after a March 16 referendum. They hope to attract Russian producers. - Russia will insist on the fulfillment of a Feb. 21 agreement between the West and Ukraine's Viktor Yanukovich during a meeting of Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov and U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry scheduled for Friday. NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA www.ng.ru - Belarus has demonstrated its readiness to join Russia in its conflict with Ukraine, the daily says, adding that Belarus has allowed Russian soldiers to land on its territory. - Russia's opposition has invited Maidan activists and Ukraine's former prime minister Yulia Tymoshenko to join an anti-war rally to protest in Moscow on Saturday, the daily says.  ROSSIISKAYA GAZETA www.rg.ru - Russia will increase the number of servicemen and its combat ability at its military base in Tajikistan to oppose possible threats from Afghanistan after international troops leave the country this year, the daily says. - Numerous armed groups across Ukraine, which say they defended Maidan protesters, are trying to make money through rackets and robberies, the daily says, reporting on a number of cases of attacks on commercial banks by armed people including Russia's Sberbank <SBER.MM> office in Vinnitsa.  MOSKOVSKY KOMSOMOLETS www.mk.ru